Here's how to handle each scenario with modern MSTest (3.9+):

## 1. Windows-only (registry tests)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
public void Registry_ReadsExpectedValue()
{
    var value = Registry.GetValue(@"HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\...", "Key", null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(value);
}
```

## 2. Skip in CI (requires local GPU)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]
public void RenderFrame_ProducesExpectedOutput()
{
    // Only runs locally, skipped in CI
}
```

## 3. Flaky external API (retry)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)]
[Timeout(10000)]
public async Task WeatherApi_ReturnsForecast(TestContext testContext)
{
    var result = await _client.GetForecastAsync(testContext.CancellationToken);
    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
}
```

## 4. Temp files that must be cleaned up

Use `[TestCleanup]` — it runs even if the test fails:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class FileProcessorTests
{
    private string _tempFile = string.Empty;

    [TestInitialize]
    public void Setup()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void ProcessFile_WritesExpectedContent()
    {
        FileProcessor.Process(_tempFile);
        Assert.AreEqual("expected", File.ReadAllText(_tempFile));
    }

    [TestCleanup]
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

Alternatively, implement `IDisposable` — MSTest calls `Dispose` after each test (after `[TestCleanup]`):

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class FileProcessorTests : IDisposable
{
    private readonly string _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();

    public void Dispose()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

---

**Minimum versions:** `[OSCondition]` and `[CICondition]` require MSTest 3.10+; `[Retry]` requires 3.9+. All need the `MSTest` package or `MSTest.Sdk`.
